The Stage of May
London —— Facing the newly appointed British Prime Minister Theresa May is a formidable task: to carry out the voters' demand of "Brexit" by the people of Britain —— or more accurately, England and Wales —— and manage the far-reaching consequences that this task entails.
This challenge she faces dwarfs those faced by her predecessors in recent years.
But she may have the capability to accomplish this task.
No one should underestimate May.
Like German Chancellor Merkel, who has already demonstrated courage in a series of crises, Theresa May has all the tools needed to complete the task in her hands.
She is intelligent and tenacious, and has no patience for nonsense.
She has a strong sense of public service and equally strong values.
Unbound by any ideology, she is very good at taking control and acts within self-imposed boundaries to ensure she is familiar with the issues she is dealing with.
May has won most of the battles she has been involved in, and is merciless to those who have treated her with underhanded tactics.
But she has made few enemies within the party and is quite popular among ordinary members.
This is a powerful combination —— one she needs to make full use of to lead Britain's Brexit process.
There is no doubt that the Brexit process has already begun.
Even though Scotland and Northern Ireland voted to remain in the EU, May has repeatedly stated that the Brexit referendum cannot be reversed.
She has repeatedly stated that "Brexit means Brexit," and her ministers under her have also supported her view.
But May has yet to give an exact definition of Brexit for Britain.
This task is very difficult to accomplish.
Imagine someone telling you, "Breakfast is breakfast," and then starting to prepare food for you.
You would find it hard to clearly know exactly what you are going to eat.
A Northern Ireland "Ulster fry" —— eggs, bacon, sausage, black pudding, potatoes, soda bread, and fried tomatoes —— with a cup of tea?
Coffee and pastries?
Depending on your environment and personal preferences, you may feel very differently about various possible combinations.
The same applies to Brexit in the UK.
Some may primarily focus on preventing EU labor from entering the UK.
Others may be more concerned about securing access to the single market.
But unlike breakfast, the UK cannot order every single dish on the menu.
The reality often overlooked by the Brexit supporters is that the EU will not give Britain benefits for free.
This is not because EU leaders want to win favor or punish Britain for rejecting the EU (such incendiary rhetoric sometimes dominates, such as the new British Foreign Secretary Boris Johnson's claim of "Hitler-style imperialism").
On the contrary, we Britons often forget that everyone — including the EU and all its member states — has their own political or commercial interests they swear to protect.
For May, the core challenge over the next few months will be to determine what Britain's goals should be, based on reality, after the difficult negotiations on its relationship with the EU (and thus with the world) begin in the trade sector?
Given the scope of the agenda (I can think of at least six major topics that need to be negotiated separately), the negotiation process may take several years to complete.
(When the negotiations are completed, my 11-year-old granddaughter may already be starting university!
) We must clearly define our priorities to prevent the negotiations from dragging on even longer.
The goal is certainly to achieve a balance between allowing British goods and services (especially financial services) to enter other European countries and restricting the entry of EU citizens into the UK.
The more negotiators gain in one area, the greater the concessions they need to make in other areas.
May needs to make full use of her knowledge, skills, and political capital to ensure the reasonableness of the negotiation deal.
But even if she succeeds in achieving her goals, she will still find that the discontent is not only among some parts —— a result that is inevitable —— but among all.
This will exacerbate another major challenge facing May's government: narrowing the growing chasm in British society exposed by Brexit.
The blue-collar workers in the north and central parts of England were the main force behind the Brexit referendum; they have always been distant from political leaders, left behind by globalization, and marginalized by globalization's so-called agent —— the EU.
The metropolitan areas of England —— especially London —— may have benefited greatly from globalization, but they have not received any of the benefits.
Due to a lack of confidence in the Labour Party led by left-wing leader Jeremy Corbyn, many members of the blue-collar working class ultimately fell prey to the promises of Brexit populism.
"We will reverse globalization," they said.
"We will drive out immigrants who keep wages low and transfer hundreds of millions of pounds originally given to the EU into public services."
They promised that Brexit would allow Britain to return to a safer and more prosperous past.
Brexit supporters cannot truly fulfill these promises.
Globalization cannot be reversed, nor can the influx of immigrants from the EU be cut off.
Any such measures would only destroy British businesses.
Even if economic downturns lead to a decrease in immigration, the workers who voted for Brexit may still feel disheartened to find that low-paying jobs remain low-paying and the pressure on public services remains heavy.
This is unlikely to lead to an improvement in social cohesion.
The Brexit referendum has already triggered a populist emotional storm that is difficult to control.
Just as Donald Trump is unable to improve the situation of working-class voters in America, no matter how the situation may appear, Brexit is also entirely incapable of bringing benefits to those who chose it.
Despite having many advantages, such challenges may still be beyond May's ability to overcome.
